{
  "doc_id": "56028",
  "text": "In general, cerebral hemorrhage occurs more frequently in the elderly than in the young. Previous studies in rats have shown that, during cerebral stroke, the overall mortality rate was much higher in old rats than in young rats. [CITATION_1] Little is known about the effect of aging on hemorragic brain damage, although hippocampal tissue from old animals was recently reported to be more susceptible to ischemia-reoxygenation injury. [CITATION_2] Furthermore, ICH caused greater brain edema and neurological deficits in aged than in younger rats, [CITATION_3] suggesting that aging may have a profound effect on ICH-induced brain injury.",
